    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1873273163" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1873273163" />
    <a title="Denton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7820078-denton"><img alt="Denton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1329662900p2/7820078.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1873273163?book_show_action=true">Jan 09, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Denton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Denton" href="/user/show/7820078-denton">Denton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1873273163" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15187789521957675831">This is one of the worst books I have ever read in my life. While I respect J.D. Vance&apos;s self-identification as Appalachian based on his family ties to Kentucky, Vance shows in this book that he has little if any understanding of the Appalachian region or its people. In fact, he appears to have little understanding of any section of the world. Poverty is a problem in Appalachia, but not everyone in the region is impoverished. Many people in the region and in America are descended from Scots-Iris</span>
  <span id="freeText15187789521957675831" style="display:none">This is one of the worst books I have ever read in my life. While I respect J.D. Vance's self-identification as Appalachian based on his family ties to Kentucky, Vance shows in this book that he has little if any understanding of the Appalachian region or its people. In fact, he appears to have little understanding of any section of the world. Poverty is a problem in Appalachia, but not everyone in the region is impoverished. Many people in the region and in America are descended from Scots-Irish ancestors, but not all Appalachians are Scots-Irish, and being Scots-Irish does not make them all "hillbillies." Drugs are a problem in Appalachia, but they are a national problem. I feel sorry for Mr. Vance that his view of the world is so narrow; he sees every deficiency in his own life as stemming directly from his grandparents' connection to and migration from Appalachia. The out-migration was difficult for many, but many also found success in their lives, and many others in Appalachia didn't migrate and led very successful lives. Many of the issues Vance writes about are class issues that occur in various forms all over the world, but Vance lumps everyone in Appalachia as poor hillbillies. Shockingly little (of value) is said about class. It is sad that this book, which has such a narrow, ill-informed viewpoint of the world, has garnered so much attention. But books that pander to stereotypes always seem to draw readers. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15187789521957675831" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

